issue.title: Filename not passed to the typescript formatter
issue.body:
The default typescript formatter is:

`let g:formatdef_tsfmt = '"tsfmt --stdin %"'`

Which has for effect to call `tsfmt` with `%` as a filename (instead of the actual filename). This is a problem for `.tsx` files which are not formatted properly.

This can be checked by setting the formatter with verbose mode:

`let g:formatdef_tsfmt = '"tsfmt --verbose --stdin %"'`

and then after a format, there is at the top of the formatted file:

`file: %`

Which means the filename wasn't passed.

issue.title: Loady doesn't handle columns with newlines in them
issue.body:
Because loady reads lines using the `IO#each` function [here](https://github.com/teeparham/loady/blob/9fb8db71e43066dd6be8c7b429436930f8d9163a/lib/loady/csv_loader.rb#L23) it doesn't read a full CSV row if any of the columns contain a newline.

It would be better to use [CSV.foreach](http://ruby-doc.org/stdlib-1.9.2/libdoc/csv/rdoc/CSV.html#method-c-foreach) to loop over the rows. The CSV library reads a full row even when there are newlines in the middle of a row.

issue.title: Add a @Dirty annotation
issue.body:
I've been trying to find some way of creating simple classes with getters and setters that can track changes. What I'm thinking is that when Lombok  encounters a class with `@Dirty`, the setter methods would be written in such a way that the changes are added to an internal map.

The following methods would then be added:

`boolean isDirty()`
`Map<String,Object> getChanges()`
`void reset()`

Of course this would only work for `@Data` and not `@Value`. It would be a little more complex, but if a builder was involved and had `toBuilder=true`, then the builder could copy the values and flag a change is the builder overrides the value. This would then work for immutable classes with `@Value`.

issue.title: How to use for more level field?
Pass in additional args to JVM on install
issue.body:
Some jars require additional arguments to be supplied every time the project is run.

For example, in order to run Leiningen, the Clojure jar must be run as the main entry point to Java, and then an additional argument "-m" must be given to tell Clojure where it's own entry point is, in this case "leiningen.core.main".

Since this argument must be supplied every time the project is called, it only makes sense to add an additional argument to the install command which will put that static command into the generated startup script. Something like "-a" for arguments or "-s" for startup or something followed by the additional arguments to add after the classpath.

issue.title: Upon restart OSDs sometimes start in a bad state

In the bare metal scenario we frequently see an issue when restarting a machine that one or two of the OSDs are started in a state where they are not responding even though the OSD process is running. Ceph marks them as down.

issue.title: FPU registers with exponent values exceeding those of float64 are shown as 0 or inf
issue.body:
Here's an [example FASM code](https://pastebin.mozilla.org/8839973) and [checking code in C++](https://pastebin.mozilla.org/8839974). If running the fasm example, the first `fld` loads approximately `3.25435e-763`, which EDB shows as `0`. The second load is of approximately `-3.46264e+383`, which EDB shows as `-inf`.

Apparently, somewhere in the middle of processing the numbers are converted to double, thus losing representation range.

Running the C++ snippet you can check that the values are actually in the range of `float80`.

What's funny, GDB (at least 7.7.1) has exactly the same issue :)

issue.title: Errors when trying to package web extension
issue.body:
I have **web-ext@1.2.4** installed globally and am getting errors when I call `$ make build_only`.

```sh
$ make build_only

rm ./build/*.xpi
web-ext build --source-dir=src --artifacts-dir=build
Building web extension from /Users/pdehaan/dev/github/FirefoxNoMore404s/src
Your web extension is ready: build/wayback_machine-1.4.3.zip
mv build/wayback_machine-"1.4.3".xpi build/Wayback_Machine_Firefox_V"1.4.3".xpi
mv: rename build/wayback_machine-1.4.3.xpi to build/Wayback_Machine_Firefox_V1.4.3.xpi: No such file or directory
make: *** [build_only] Error 1
```

According to [**Getting started with web-ext:** Packaging your extension](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/Add-ons/WebExtensions/Getting_started_with_web-ext#Packaging_your_extension), running `$ web-ext build` will:

> ... output a full path to the generated **.zip** file that can be loaded into a browser.

So it looks like the Makefile is expecting `web-ext` to produce an .XPI file, but `web-ext` is generating .ZIP files.

issue.title: A parent state's resolves are resolved twice when a child state's resolve are rejected on initial run
issue.body:
I came across this subtle bug while implementing two distinct "zones" in my app -- namely a "visitors only" zone and a "members only" zone. This is tested with Angular 1.5.1 and UI Router 0.2.18

Consider this scenario:
- **root state** is an abstract state that dynamically loads (through a resolve) the current user's profile. This resolve is injected into direct child states to make sure they're not instanciated before the profile is finished loading
- **child state 1**'s own resolve checks if the user is registered. If so, the resolve is rejected and the user redirected to **child state 2**
- **child state 2**'s own resolve checks if the user is _not_ registered. If so, the resolve is rejected and the user redirected to **child state 1**

So, in effect: **child state 1** is my "visitors only" zone while **child state 2** is my "members only" zone.

Now, assume I am a registered user. When I first launch the app, here's what happens:

1. **root state** is resolved, my user profile is loaded
2. **child state 1**'s resolve is rejected (since I'm a member) and I am redirected to **child state 2**
3. **root state** is resolved again! (and the API to load the profile is called again...)
4. **child state 2**' is resolved and successfully activated

In my understanding, step 3 shouldn't happen -- **root**'s already been resolved previously and should not be resolved gain. Or am I getting something wrong?

Note this only happens on the app's initial launch; if I try to navigate to **state 1** (eg. by clicking an `ui-sref`), then only **state 1**'s resolve is tested and correctly rejected without **root state** being resolved again.

I've made a Plunker to demonstrate: https://plnkr.co/edit/Nne19FArvUf0W4JHOtB7

probe: Stats gathering can be started twice
issue.body:
In `probe/docker/container.go`, `StartGatheringStats()`, we check if `c.statsConn` is set and only start a new stats connection if it is not. However, we do not immediately then set this value (that happens only after some other setup inside a goroutine we then launch), meaning it might not be set by the time we get called again.
In this case, we would have two connections reporting stats for the same probe.

The simplest fix would be to add a `statsStarted bool` to the struct, and do:
```go
c.Lock()
if c.statsStarted {
  c.Unlock()
  return nil
}
c.statsStarted = true
c.Unlock()
```
perhaps modulo some nicer handling of the Unlock
